2026-06-29 | Maximum Dot Product by Inserting Zeros

	Question
Return the maximum possible dot product.
	Key Insight
We cannot change the order of elements in b.
For every element of a, we have two choices:
•	Skip it
	This means we insert a zero in b at this position.
•	Match it with the current element of b
	and move to the next element in both arrays.
This naturally leads to Dynamic Programming.
	State Definition
		dp[i][j]
	= Maximum dot product using:
		a[i...n−1]
	and
		b[j...m−1]
	Transition
	Option 1: Skip a[i]
		dp[i+1][j]
	Option 2: Match
		a[i] × b[j]
		+
		dp[i+1][j+1]
	Take the maximum.
	Base Cases
	If all elements of b are matched:
		dp[i][m] = 0
	If elements of a finish before b:
		impossible
		return −∞
	Approach
1.	Create a DP table.
2.	Process states from the end.
3.	At each state:
			skip current element of a
		or
			match current elements
4.	Return dp[0][0].
	Time Complexity
	O(n × m)
	Space Complexity
	O(n × m)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxDotProduct(int n, int m,
                      vector<int>& a,
                      vector<int>& b) {
        const long long NEG = -(1LL << 60);
        vector<vector<long long>> dp(
            n + 1,
            vector<long long>(m + 1, NEG));
        for(int i = 0; i <= n; i++)
            dp[i][m] = 0;
        for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            for(int j = m - 1; j >= 0; j--) {
                long long skip = dp[i + 1][j];
                long long take = NEG;
                if(dp[i + 1][j + 1] != NEG) {
                    take = 1LL * a[i] * b[j]
                         + dp[i + 1][j + 1];
                }
                dp[i][j] = max(skip, take);
            }
        }
        return dp[0][0];
    }
};
	Space Optimized Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int maxDotProduct(int n, int m,
                      vector<int>& a,
                      vector<int>& b) {
        const long long NEG = -(1LL << 60);
        vector<long long> next(m + 1, NEG);
        vector<long long> curr(m + 1, NEG);
        next[m] = 0;
        for(int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            curr[m] = 0;
            for(int j = m - 1; j >= 0; j--) {
                long long skip = next[j];
                long long take = NEG;
                if(next[j + 1] != NEG) {
                    take = 1LL * a[i] * b[j]
                         + next[j + 1];
                }
                curr[j] = max(skip, take);
            }
            swap(curr, next);
        }
        return next[0];
    }
};
	Key Insight
	Each element of `a` either:
	- gets matched with the current element of `b`, contributing `a[i] × b[j]`, or
	- is skipped, which is equivalent to inserting a `0` at that position in `b`.
	Since the order of elements in `b` cannot change, Dynamic Programming over the indices of both arrays gives the optimal solution in **O(n × m)** time.
